<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-461-392  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 461 392.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 22 1990 v7 n20 p26(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Tool automates PC tasks for unattended operation. (ComplementarySolutions Inc introduces Automate/Anytime utility for unattendedprocessing) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Complementary Solutions Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Automate/Anytime (Utility program) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersUtility ProgramsSoftware packagesProduct IntroductionBatch ProcessingBack-Up SystemsMemory-Resident Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Complementary Solutions Inc. plans to ship next month a new utility thatallows PCs to operate on automatic pilot.andM;Intended for batch processing, backup and printing applications, the $149Automate/Anytime utility lets users set up daily, weekly and monthly timeslots during which their PCs operate without supervision.andM;The Federal Home Loan Bank of Cincinnati, for one, is using Automate/Anywhereto automate data processing for an asset/ liability application, according toSteven Ruwe, a support technician at the bank.andM;Automate/Anywhere remains resident in 13K bytes of memory to track the PC'sclock and start tasks at preset times.andM;If a scheduled batch job is ready to begin when the computer is in use,Automate/ Anywhere pops up a window that inquires whether the user wants torun the automated task.andP;  If the job is set to take place when an applicationis still running, the software will swap the screen data to a disk file andreturn it when the scheduled task is completed.andM;Complementary Solutions can be contacted in Atlanta at (404) 454-8033.andO;</TEXT></DOC>